Division III Baseball Batting Statistics as Predictors for Runs Scored

Hardy Smith and Will Guzman

2023-04-24

Abstract

In baseball, the outcome of the game is determined by the team that scores the most runs. For decades, coaches, players, and fans have argued which batting statistic is the most important to the total number of runs a team scores. In this experiment, we looked at which batting statistics had the biggest impact on the total runs scored. To do this, we ran linear regression models to see which had the strongest correlation. By using data from Division III baseball to model these relationships, more specifically data from the Southern Athletic Association (Rhodes’ conference) and the New England Small College Conference, it allowed us to see concrete relationships between these variables and bring insight to this heavily debated subject.

Introduction and Terminology

What is the most important batting statistic in baseball? Over the past two decades, with the takeover and growing prominence of data analytics in the sport of baseball, teams have researched and argued which statistic most efficiently and abundantly indicates more runs scored.

We wanted to find out, in Division III baseball, which batting statistic: batting average (AVG), on-base percentage (OBP), or slugging percentage (SLGP), has the greatest relationship with players scoring more runs. To find the answer to this question, we looked at the relationship (through multiple linear regression models) between a players’ total runs scored and each of these statistics to see which had the strongest correlation.

Before we get into our data, it is important to define some key variables in our experiment. First looking at our response variables which is a players’ total runs scored. Runs are measured in increments of 1, increasing by 1 every time a player crosses home plate, thus, the range of possible values will be positive integers, including 0, to some number less than 100; considering the length of the Division III baseball season, scoring more than 100 is nearly impossible. This value will likely have an average somewhere around 20 runs for Division III baseball players with recorded statistics. Next looking at our explanatory variables which are a player’s batting average (AVG), on-base percentage (OBP), and slugging percentage (SLGP). A player’s batting average is a quantitative value, measured as a percentage, calculated by dividing a player’s hits by his total at-bats (located under the AVG column). Slugging Percentage is also quantitative value, measured as a percentage, that represents the total number of bases a player records per at-bat, essentially equating to being a “big hitter” if you have a higher SLGP. The exact formula for slugging percentage is: (1B + 2Bx2 + 3Bx3 + HRx4)/AB (located under SLGP column). Lastly, On-Base Percentage, a quantitative value, measured as a percentage, that represents the percentage that a player gets on base in any form, including hit by pitch or base on balls (located under OBP column). The full formula is as follows (Hits + Walks + Hit by Pitch) / (At Bats + Walks + Hit by Pitch + Sacrifice Flies)

Data and Hypothesis

We collected our data from the Southern Athletic Association and New England Small College Athletic Conference–the two conferences keep archives of BA, OBP, and SLGP dating back several years. We compiled each of those statistics from the 2022 season from every player on each team’s roster from those archives and put them into an Excel File to use for our modeling and calculations. These statistics can be found on each conference’s athletic website.The sample will be the baseball players in the NESCAC and SAA with recorded batting statistics from the 2022 baseball season. This came out to be 338 observational units; however, after cleaning and wrangling our data, we ended up with a sample of 266. We are hoping to generalize for all Division III baseball players, and with 374 Division III baseball teams carrying an average of 34 players, we are generalizing to a population of around 12,716 individuals. We hypothesize that a player’s on-base percentage will be the batting statistic that has the strongest relationship with their total runs scored. As mentioned earlier, we are using multiple linear regression models to determine this statistic. In addition to this, we will look at how the relationships of the data are similar or differ between conferences to see if the relationships hold across conferences.

Here we are removing outliers based off the visualization and boxplots. Several players in the data set had skewed statistics. For example, if a player had few at bats, they might have had an on base percentage of 100%, but scored 0 runs. This is misleading, so we filtered out abnormally low or abnormally high batting statistics that may be indicative of having had few at bats.

d3BaseballClean <- d3BaseballClean %>%
  filter(AVG <= 0.49 & AVG >= 0.1, SLGP <= 0.75 & SLGP >= 0.25, OBP <= 0.59 & OBP >= 0.21)

Transforming data

d3BaseballClean <- d3BaseballClean %>%
  mutate(
    AVG = sqrt(AVG),
    SLGP = sqrt(SLGP),
    OBP = sqrt(OBP)
    )

Model

Here we define a multiple linear regression model for the data set containing data from 266 players in both the SAA and NESCAC.

model <- lm(R~AVG+SLGP+OBP, data = d3BaseballClean)

Checking diagnostics

plot(model, which = 1)

plot(model, which = 2)

plot(model, which = 3)

Model summary

summary(model)

Results

Observing this multiple linear regression model which shows the relationship between a player’s total runs scored and their batting statistics (AVG, SLGP, OBP), we can see clear positive relationships between runs and each statistic. The regression equation being \(R = -63.956 + 45.705(AVG) + 52.522(SLGP) + 38.594(OBP)\). Also, the p-values for AVG and SLGP are both statistically significant \((p < 0.5)\), while the p-value for OBP is marginally significant \((p=0.0511)\). However, the adjusted R-squared is 0.319, which tells us that 31.9% of the variability in runs can be explained by our three statistics. This may not seem very high, but in the context of sports statistics, it can still be considered meaningful, indicating that the model explains a significant portion of the variability in runs. Moreover, our p-value for our F-statistics is very low (p=2.2e-16), which tells us that the model as a whole is statistically significant. Looking at the residual and normality plots, we can say that our residuals exhibit a relatively stable pattern, as in the residual plot, we can see the points evenly distributed along that zero line. Also, in the normality plot, we can see the points closely follow the expected line, showing us that our data meets the conditions of normality. With only a few outliers potentially skewing the data, we can say that all conditions for our residuals and normality are met. Thus, we can conclude that slugging percentage slightly beats out the other two batting statistics as the most powerful predictor. So, for every percentage point increase in slugging percentage (0.01), our expected runs will increase by 0.52522 runs.

Results

This model once again brings forth differing results, with batting average being the most significant predictor for runs. We see clear positive relationships between runs and each statistic. the regression equation being \(R = -53.702 + 49.335(AVG) + 38.210(SLGP) + 31.694(OBP)\). Also, the p-values for AVG and SLGP are both statistically significant \((p < 0.5)\), while the p-value for OBP is not significant \((p=0.18374)\). Our R-squared and F-statistics p-value, and residual and normality plots once again remain consistent with the other two models, indicating the model as whole is a powerful predictor. But in this case, we conclude that batting average is the most significant predictor for runs. For every percentage point increase in batting average (0.01), our expected runs will increase by 0.49335 runs, and batting average beats out slugging percentage as the best predictor for runs in this model.

Conclusion

From our models, we conclude that instead of generalizing to the entirety of Division III baseball; we see that play styles and the importance of different batting statistics can differ between conferences. Overall, we observe that slugging percentage and batting average are the better predictors in comparison to on-base percentage; although we conjecture that some discrepancies in the data may be playing a part in that observation. However, our findings lead us towards the general statement that pitching in Division III is levels below what you may see at the Division I level, especially in terms of depth of bullpens. Thus, swinging the bat and getting hits is a necessary feature of most Division III offenses, as opposed to walking or getting hit by pitches. There are less strikeouts, making it evident why batting average or slugging percentage would be the most predictive factors in earning more runs.

Moreover, it is interesting to observe that when comparing the SAA and NESCAC, slugging percentage is clearly the better predictor for runs in the SAA, while batting average trumps slugging percentage in the NESCAC. Is there legitimacy to the claim the “big-hitters” are more beneficial for teams in the SAA as opposed to the NESCAC? We don’t know. More research and modeling would need to be done to get a clearer look into this problem. Moving forward, we feel that more forethought into building out data set could lead to better results and better predictive power in our models. For example, filtering players out of the data set if they had below a certain number of at-bats during the season, or something along those lines. But in conclusion, the models we built hold relatively significant predictive power into telling us which batting statistics might be the most beneficial for Division III baseball teams and players, especially those in the SAA and NESCAC.
